#### What is Big Data?  

First of all, the term “Big Data” does not refer to actual data. It is a field that treats ways to analyze, systematically extract information from, or deal with datasets that are too large or complex.  

![](https://www.theschool.ai/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/meme1.png)

We should Definity know about the four big V’s of big data.  

- **Volume-based value:** I would call this meaning full volume because mere a huge volume of data does not mean that we have a big value for it. The more comprehensive your integrated view of the customer and the more historical data you have on them, the more insight you can extract from it. In turn, you are making better decisions when it comes to acquiring, retaining, growing and managing those customer relationships. 
- **Velocity-based value:** The more rapidly you can process information into your data and analytics platform, the more flexibility you get to find answers to your questions via queries, reports, dashboards, etc. A rapid data ingestion and rapid analysis capability provides you with the timely and correct decision achieve your customer relationship management objectives. 
- **Variety-based value:** The more varied customer data you have – from the CRM system, social media, call-center logs, etc. – the more multifaceted view you develop about your customers, thus enabling you to develop customer journey maps and personalization to engage more with customers. 
- **Veracity-based value:** Amassing a lot of data does not mean the data becomes clean and accurate. Data on customers must remain consolidated, cleansed, consistent, and current to make the right decisions. 

![](https://www.theschool.ai/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/4-Vs-of-big-data-1024x629.jpg)

Ok now let’s move to the second buzz word Hadoop.  

#### What is Hadoop? 

The Apache™ Hadoop® is a framework that will help developers to process large datasets across clusters of computers using simple programming models in a distributed environment. The library is designed in such a fashion so it can scale up from a single server to thousands of computing powers. The library is also able to detect and handle failures at the application layer so we need not rely on the hardware to report back. This allows Hadoop to deliver a highly available service on top of a cluster of machines.   

![](https://www.theschool.ai/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/bm0moq0cyaavb_t1.png)

Hadoop software library consists of a set of modules that will make the above statements true.  

Modules 

The project includes these modules: 

- **Hadoop Common:** The common utilities that support the other Hadoop modules. 
- **Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS™):** A distributed file system that provides high-throughput access to application data. 
- **Hadoop YARN:** A framework for job scheduling and cluster resource management. 
- **Hadoop MapReduce:** A YARN-based system for parallel processing of large data sets. 
- **[Hadoop Ozone](https://hadoop.apache.org/ozone/): An object store for Hadoop.**
- **[Hadoop Submarine](https://hadoop.apache.org/submarine/): A machine learning engine for Hadoop.**


#### Why do we need Hadoop?  

![](https://www.theschool.ai/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/bigdata.jpg)

The main and important feature of Hadoop is to allow users to do analytics n huge unstructured data. Simply Hadoop will help us handle big data.  


How Hadoop is doing this?  

Let’s learn about 3 important modules of the Hadoop ecosystem.  

HDFS – Hadoop Distributed File System.   

 This is a data storage module that will allow users to access terabytes of data across all the nodes in a Hadoop cluster. HDFS separates large volumes of data into data blocks that are managed from various interfaces in the cluster. Each data block is copied to multiple hardware locations so that a single machine failure does not result in a loss of data availability. 

Follow this link to learn more. https://hadoop.apache.org/docs/current1/hdfs_design.html 

![](https://www.theschool.ai/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/hdfsarchitecture.gif)

#### Hadoop Map Reduce.  

The term “MapReduce” refers to two different tasks that Hadoop application performs. Mapper takes a part of a dataset and converts it into another set of data, where individual elements are broken down into tuples (key/value pairs). The reducer takes the output from a map as input and joins those key-value pairs into a smaller set of tuples.  

In this diagram, you can see how the data is being split and the mapper is segregating the job and finally reducer summarizes it before declaring the results. The main beauty of MapReduce in Hadoop is to parallelize massively across all nodes of the cluster which allows the sorting of petabytes of data in a few hours.   

![](https://www.theschool.ai/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/Map-Reduce-Flow-768x357.png)

#### Hadoop YARN – Yet Another Resource Negotiator 

Yarn allows different data processing engines like graph processing, interactive processing, stream processing as well as batch processing to run and process data stored in Hadoop Distributed File System. Apart from resource management, Yarn also does job Scheduling. Yarn extends the power of Hadoop to other evolving technologies, so they can take the advantages of HDFS (most reliable and popular storage system on the planet) and economic cluster. 

![](data:image/png;base64,)
##### hadoop yarn architecture tutorial

Hadoop yarn architecture 

Apache yarn is also a data operating system for Hadoop. This architecture of Hadoop provides a general-purpose data processing platform which is not just limited to the MapReduce. It enables Hadoop to process other purpose-built data processing system other than MapReduce. It allows running several different frameworks on the same hardware where Hadoop is deployed. 

![](https://www.theschool.ai/wp-content/uploads/2019/04/YARNArch.png)

To Learn more about Yarn follow this link https://hadoop.apache.org/docs/current/hadoop-yarn/hadoop-yarn-site/YARN.html.
